english:
  title: Record of Seungryeon Temple
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Namwon Prefecture is celebrated by many for its beautiful mountains and waters. Buddhist monks have established temples throughout this region, each claiming the most distinguished sites, yet Seungryeon Temple stands foremost among them all. So spoke Lord Jung Munho to me, and he further requested, through a letter from the great Zen master Gagyun who serves as abbot, that I compose a record of the temple's origins and development. I have long regretted my inability to visit such fine landscapes and leave my name among them—a genuine wish of mine. Moreover, I have long admired the virtue of Master Gagyun, and so I gladly undertake this account.

    The temple stands some thirty li northeast of the prefecture. Its former name was Geumgang Temple, though the era of its founding remains unknown. A certain National Teacher Honghye, whose given name was Junggaeng, retired there after his time at the Inner Vow Hall, yet the buildings were humble and cramped. Though he once wished to expand them, he could not. After his passing, the great Zen master Juram, whose name was Yeonon, came as the elder of Jokye with the endorsement of Honghye's disciples. They united in appointing Juram as abbot. Juram immediately surveyed the work and managed the funds, while one Jonghun supervised the gathering of offerings from the faithful. The temple's name was changed to Seungryeon, with construction beginning in the year Eulchuk and completed in spring of Sinchuk. The Buddha hall, monks' quarters, refectory, meditation chambers, guest lodges, storehouse, and kitchen numbered one hundred and eleven rooms in total. Every implement for chanting sutras and every daily necessity was provided without lack—all accomplished through Juram's accumulated resources and Jonghun's tireless efforts. An image of Amitabha Buddha was enshrined in the center of the main hall, wholly undertaken by Juram himself, while the printing and storage of the complete Buddhist canon on either side resulted from the collective offerings of the townspeople. Several servants, whom Juram had inherited from his parents, were also dedicated to the temple. In autumn of the year Musul, as his end drew near, Juram entrusted the temple's affairs to Master Gagyun, who was both his nephew in kinship and his dharma heir. The outer walls, which had remained unfinished, were constructed by the master, and by summer of the year Gyemyo, all the temple's works were complete.

    I reflect thus: It is customary for the Buddhist order not merely to adorn their dwellings but to ensure their transmission to future generations. Now, as for the names Geumgang and Seungryeon—which holds greater significance, which lesser, that one must be chosen and the other forsaken? Yet Juram's deliberate change of the temple's name signifies a new beginning—that this becomes the first generation, passed down to a second, and continuing thus through a hundred and thousand generations without alteration. Surely such vision reaches far into the future. In transmitting it to Master Gagyun through both kinship and dharma, Juram left nothing to be desired. Yet I cannot know whether Master Gagyun will find worthy successors, nor whether they will preserve what their teacher established as faithfully. I fear that with each passing generation, the original intention may slip further from grasp. Still, if only in the ages to come—through countless generations—the grounds of Seungryeon remain free from thorns and desolation, that would suffice. Whether transmission continues through blood or through dharma, I dare not presume to know.

    Juram was of the Yu clan, great-grandson of the retired Premier Yu Gyeong, younger brother of the same mother as Inspector Yu Jeong, and grandson through his mother of the Minister of密直司 Lee Jonbi. He participated in the Four Selections for Buddhist Scholars, passed the examination with highest honors, dwelt in many renowned mountains, and his reputation for virtue became widespread. Master Gagyun is Juram's nephew, profound in learning, exemplary in conduct, and exquisite in calligraphy—of him his contemporaries said, "The blue surpasses the indigo."

    Recorded in the sixth month of the twenty-fourth year of Zhizheng.
  footnotes:
    - Zhizheng (至正) refers to the Mongol Yuan Dynasty period, with the twenty-fourth year corresponding to 1364 CE.
    - The phrase 'blue surpasses the indigo' is a classical Chinese idiom suggesting that the student exceeds the master.
    - Jokye (曹溪) refers to the Jogye Order, the predominant Zen Buddhist tradition in Korea.
